## PROJECT FILES — CHECK FIRST (saves you from getting it wrong)

Tesslate Studio auto-scaffolds the SDK helper into every new project.
**Before you write any fetch / HTTP code, look for these files and import
from them — they have the correct env-var names and URL pattern baked in:**

- `lib/opensailData.ts`        — Next.js + plain JS projects
- `src/lib/opensailData.ts`    — Vite-built projects
- `opensail_data.py`           — Python projects
- `.env.example`               — every project (lists the exact env-var names)

If the file exists: import `serverData` (Route Handlers / server actions) or
`browserData` ('use client' components) from `lib/opensailData` and call its
`insert / list / get / update / delete` methods. Do NOT write your own
`fetch` to the Data API — you will get the URL pattern wrong.

Only fall back to the API shape below if the file is genuinely missing.

---

## CRITICAL — USE THESE EXACT NAMES (no other variants will work)

The deploy injector ONLY writes env vars under these exact names. If you use any
other name (e.g. `WORKSPACE_DATA_URL`, `DATA_API_BASE`, `WORKSPACE_DATA_SERVICE_KEY`,
`COLLECTION_ID`, etc.), the deployed app will get **empty values** and break.

**Environment variable contract — copy verbatim:**

| Runtime | URL var | KEY var |
|---|---|---|
| Server (Next.js Route Handler, FastAPI, Go, plain Node) | `OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` | `OPENSAIL_DATA_KEY` |
| Vite-built frontend (browser) | `VITE_OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` | `VITE_OPENSAIL_DATA_KEY` |
| Next.js **client** components | `NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` | `NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENSAIL_DATA_KEY` |

**HTTP API URL pattern — NO `/collections/` prefix, NO `/records` suffix:**

```
POST   ${OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL}/{collection_name}                  insert
GET    ${OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL}/{collection_name}?limit=&offset=   list
GET    ${OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL}/{collection_name}/{record_id}      get one
PATCH  ${OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL}/{collection_name}/{record_id}      replace
DELETE ${OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL}/{collection_name}/{record_id}      delete
```

All requests need header `Authorization: Bearer ${OPENSAIL_DATA_KEY}` (or the
appropriate VITE_ / NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefixed variant). JSON body for POST/PATCH.

**Response shape:**
- Single record: `{ "id": "...", "collection_id": "...", "data": {...}, "created_at": "...", "updated_at": "..." }`
- List: `{ "records": [...], "total": N, "limit": N, "offset": N }` (note `records`, NOT `items` or `data`)

**Do NOT:**
- invent any env-var name not in the table above
- prepend `/collections/` or `/records` to the URL
- use `process.env.WORKSPACE_DATA_*` (wrong) — it must be `OPENSAIL_DATA_*`
- read `data.items` from the list response (it is `data.records`)

---

## Workspace Data Store — built-in per-project KV/document database

Every OpenSail project has a built-in datastore. On deploy, the platform
auto-injects these environment variables into the deployed app — no manual
wiring needed:

| Var | Where to read from |
|-----|---------------------|
| `OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` | server-side (Node, Python, Go) |
| `OPENSAIL_DATA_KEY`     | server-side |
| `VITE_OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` / `VITE_OPENSAIL_DATA_KEY` | Vite-built frontends (browser) |
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` / `NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENSAIL_DATA_KEY` | Next.js client components |

Data is organised into **collections** of JSON **records**.

- **anon keys** (browser-safe) obey each collection's `public_insert / read / update / delete` flags. Default: insert-only.
- **service keys** (server-side only) bypass flags. Never ship a service key in a browser bundle.

## HTTP API shape

```
POST   {URL}/{collection}                JSON body          -> 201 {id, data, ...}
GET    {URL}/{collection}?limit=&offset= no body            -> 200 {records, total, limit, offset}
GET    {URL}/{collection}/{record_id}                       -> 200 {id, data, ...}
PATCH  {URL}/{collection}/{record_id}    JSON body          -> 200 {id, data, ...}     (replaces document)
DELETE {URL}/{collection}/{record_id}                       -> 204
```

All requests need `Authorization: Bearer <KEY>`. JSON body for POST/PATCH.

## Setup checklist (every app that needs persistence)

1. Call the `workspace_data` tool to `create_collection` for each collection (e.g. `submissions`, `subscribers`, `events`). For each, set `public_insert: true` if the browser writes to it; leave other public flags `false` unless you really need them.
2. Drop the SDK file for the project's language (below) into the project.
3. Use it in the app — fetch from `import.meta.env.VITE_OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` (Vite), `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` (Next.js client) or `process.env.OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL` (Node/Python/Go server).
4. On deploy, the env vars are auto-injected. Nothing else to wire.
5. For a server-side reader/writer (Next.js Route Handler, FastAPI, etc.), call the `workspace_data` tool's `create_key` action with `kind: "service"` and add it as a non-public env var.

---

## TypeScript / Vite + React — `src/lib/opensailData.ts`

```ts
const URL = import.meta.env.VITE_OPENSAIL_DATA_API_URL as string;
const KEY = import.meta.env.VITE_OPENSAIL_DATA_KEY as string;

const headers = {
  Authorization: `Bearer ${KEY}`,
  'Content-Type': 'application/json',
};

export interface Record<T = Record<string, unknown>> {
  id: string;
  collection_id: string;
  data: T;
  created_at: string;
  updated_at: string;
}

export interface Page<T = Record<string, unknown>> {
  records: Record<T>[];
  total: number;
  limit: number;
  offset: number;
}

export const data = {
  insert: <T extends object>(coll: string, doc: T): Promise<Record<T>> =>
    fetch(`${URL}/${coll}`, { method: 'POST', headers, body: JSON.stringify(doc) })
      .then((r) => { if (!r.ok) throw new Error(`insert ${r.status}`); return r.json(); }),

  list: <T extends object>(
    coll: string,
    params: { limit?: number; offset?: number } = {}
  ): Promise<Page<T>> => {
    const qs = new URLSearchParams(
      Object.fromEntries(Object.entries(params).filter(([, v]) => v !== undefined)) as Record<string, string>
    );
    return fetch(`${URL}/${coll}?${qs}`, { headers })
      .then((r) => { if (!r.ok) throw new Error(`list ${r.status}`); return r.json(); });
  },

  get: <T extends object>(coll: string, id: string): Promise<Record<T>> =>
    fetch(`${URL}/${coll}/${id}`, { headers })
      .then((r) => { if (!r.ok) throw new Error(`get ${r.status}`); return r.json(); }),

  update: <T extends object>(coll: string, id: string, doc: T): Promise<Record<T>> =>
    fetch(`${URL}/${coll}/${id}`, { method: 'PATCH', headers, body: JSON.stringify(doc) })
      .then((r) => { if (!r.ok) throw new Error(`update ${r.status}`); return r.json(); }),

  delete: (coll: string, id: string): Promise<boolean> =>
    fetch(`${URL}/${coll}/${id}`, { method: 'DELETE', headers })
      .then((r) => r.ok),
};
```

### React component using it

```tsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import { data } from './lib/opensailData';

export function ContactForm() {
  const [sent, setSent] = useState(false);
  const [err, setErr] = useState<string | null>(null);

  const submit = async (e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    const fd = new FormData(e.currentTarget);
    try {
      await data.insert('submissions', {
        email: fd.get('email'),
        message: fd.get('message'),
        ts: new Date().toISOString(),
      });
      setSent(true);
    } catch (e: unknown) {
      setErr(e instanceof Error ? e.message : 'Failed to submit');
    }
  };

  if (sent) return <p>Thanks — we got your message.</p>;
  return (
    <form onSubmit={submit}>
      <input name="email" type="email" placeholder="you@example.com" required />
      <textarea name="message" placeholder="Your message" required />
      <button type="submit">Send</button>
      {err && <p style={{ color: 'crimson' }}>{err}</p>}
    </form>
  );
}
```

### Listing records (admin view)

```tsx
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { data, type Page } from './lib/opensailData';

export function SubmissionsList() {
  const [page, setPage] = useState<Page<{ email: string; message: string }> | null>(null);
  useEffect(() => {
    data.list<{ email: string; message: string }>('submissions', { limit: 50 }).then(setPage);
  }, []);
  if (!page) return <p>Loading…</p>;
  return (
    <ul>
      {page.records.map((r) => (
        <li key={r.id}>
          <b>{r.data.email}</b>: {r.data.message}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

> Listing requires `public_read: true` on the collection (use the
> `workspace_data` tool's `update_collection` action), or call it from a
> server using a **service** key.

